default3.6.2 
defaultThe DRT scheme in Essex has overcome some of t
defaulthe challenges discussed above. Initially the service (DaRT 99) was established in May 2011 to improve access to two h
defaultospitals from the Dengie area. 
defaultThe service offers a fixed link
default 
defaultbetween Maldon, neighbouring Heybridge and Chelmsford
default 
defaulthospital, with a 
defaultdemand responsive service to outlying
default 
defaultvillages in the Dengie Peninsula. It runs between 0600 and
default 
default2100 Monday to Friday. Fares are set above the comparable
default 
defaultbus journey, reflecting the additional convenience and
default 
defaultcomfort of the service and to avoid underminin
defaultg the
default 
defaultcommercial indirect links (involving one or more changes).
default 
defaultConcessionary bus passes are accepted.
default 
defaultThe service received one-off £65,000 ‘kick start’ funding from
default the 
defaultLAA Partnership
default via RCCE
default, following a competitive tender exercise
default 
defaultcarried out by RCCE
default. It has seen increasing passenger use and viability over the
default 
defaultperiod
default and f
defaultrom May 2013, the service 
defaultwent
default fully commercial.
default 
default 
default3.6.3 
defaultThe success of the 
defaultD
default99 
defaultand the expiry of service contracts 
defaultled to the development of another DRT service in the area, 
defaultthe D5,
default which serves the most isolated parishes in the Dengie. 
defaultIt replaced a
default 
defaultconventional bus service which gave 4 off-peak return
default 
defaultjourneys on Monday - Friday and two return journeys on a
default 
defaultSaturday to the local town. DaRT 5 is a fully flexible service,
default 
defaultavailable f
defaultrom 0600 to 2000 Monday - Saturday. All journeys
default 
defaultmust be pre-booked at least one hour before travelling and
default 
defaultpassengers must be prepared to change, as the service feeds
default 
defaultinto other bus and rail services.
default 
defaultThe service was introduced following extensive consult
defaultation,
default 
defaultwhich highlighted a desire for greater choice of times and
default 
defaultdestinations.
default 
defaultThe service was expanded in October 2012 to meet demand
default 
defaultfrom a neighbouring community.
default 
default3.6.4 
defaultPassenger numbers have grown significantly. The 
defaultprevious D5 service
default 
defaultcarried an ave
defaultrage of 5 passengers per weekday and 1.5 on a
default 
defaultSaturday.
default  In July the average number of passengers per day 
defaultwas 59, and the
default cost per passenger is now down to 
defaultaround 
default£3.13p
default. 
default91% of passengers are concessionary travel pass holders. Users are deciding to make m
defaultore use of the service and are
default 
defaultintroducing new customers. For example, a single journey
default 
defaultfrom a Residential Park to the Conservative Club started off
default 
defaultas one person travelling once per week; now there are 4 or 5
default 
defaulttravelling daily. A few of the new users 
defaultpreviously used taxis.
default Some
default commuters use the service from the villages to the
default 
defaultlocal station.
default 
defaultFeedback has been very positive, with specific praise for the
default 
defaultregular driver.
default 
default3.6.5 
defaultThe service allows individuals who were previously isolated
default 
defaultto go out and be 
defaultpart of the community. There are a number
default 
defaultof older people who were unable to walk up the hill to the
default 
defaultnearest bus stop and were therefore unable to access public
default 
defaulttransport. The wide net of the DRT service has removed
default 
defaultthis problem and they are now regular tr
defaultavellers, using the
default 
defaultservice to access shops, medical
default 
defaultfacilities, clubs and social
default 
defaultevents.
default 
defaultOne lady is currently in the situation where she is unable
default 
defaultto drive or walk any distance. The door to door nature of
default 
defaultthe service has been invaluable to her. Anothe
defaultr elderly lady
default 
defaultsaid that previously her family and friends had to do all her
default 
defaultshopping for her; now she can do her own shopping. She said
default 
defaulti
defaultt has “opened up my life again” and has enabled her to choose her own food, improving her diet and consequently her he
defaultalth.
default3.6.6 
defaultConventional buses are often seen as a meeting place by
default 
defaultolder users. One concern of introducing DRT was that there
default 
defaultwouldn’t be the same opportunity to socialise. A pattern of
default 
defaultgroup booking is emerging from elderly people and people are
default 
defaultusing it
default to go out socially.
default3.6.7 
defaultA recent Age UK report highlights the importance of bus
default 
defaulttravel to not only accessing services but to contributing to
default 
defaultthe quality of life for older people
default (
defaulthttp://eprints.uwe.ac.uk/16946/
default)
default. The service may extend
default 
defaultthe time individu
defaultals can live independently, reducing health
default 
defaultand social care costs. This saving is difficult to monetise,
default 
defaultbut the cost of delaying progression to more costly care has
default 
defaultbeen valued at £181 per week (£9,412 per year). The cost
default 
defaultof an individual moving to a care
default home is valued at £27,000
default 
defaultper year. Therefore, If only three people are prevented from
default 
defaultmoving into a care home, then this service will reduce the
default 
defaultoverall cost to the public purse.
