default4.1 
defaultCurrently Essex County Council supports 12 community transport schemes across Essex; most are run as independent charitable organisations, although one is run by a district council and one is currently run in house by Essex County Council.  
default4.2 Community 
defaultTransport schemes provide transport for individuals who cannot access conventional services, whether due to restricted mobility or living in isolated areas not serviced by public transport. The quality of service provided is high, being personalised, flexi
defaultble and reliable. As a result, CT has a very high user satisfaction rating. The annual cost to the council is £1.3 million. 
default4.3 
defaultEssex County Council
default current strategy sees Community Transport as providing a safety net for those unable to access local bus s
defaultervices and thus filling in areas where conventional local bus service provision is not practicable. 
default4.4 Most CT schemes provide a range of services. These include:
default
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDial-a-ride services – demand responsive individual journeys usually carried out by access
defaultible minibuses and often by professional drivers.
default
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSocial Car services – volunteers using their own cars to provide journeys, only receiving expenses in return.
default
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultVehicle Brokerage – working with a range of different organisations to make their vehicles avail
defaultable for group hire during ‘down’ periods
default
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCommunity Buses
default - 
defaultRegistered local bus services, using larger vehicles and in the main paid drivers run under a S
defaultection 
default22 permit, often with a semi DRT element.
default4.5 
defaultT
defaulthe model employed is heavily dependent on the 
defaultuse of volunteers, both to driver and to perform ‘back office’ functions. As schemes grow, an increasing degree of 
defaultprofessionali
defaults
defaultation
default is required to manage the additional complexities of operation and ensure reliability. However, there are limits to how f
defaultar such a business model can grow due to their reliance on voluntary support.  All the schemes struggle to recruit new volunteers; often due to exacting behavioural standards required to allow a person to transport vulnerable people.  
default4.6 Currently Commun
defaultity Transport schemes receive a grant made under Service Level Agreement with ECC and in some cases with district councils
default, which 
defaultset targets for passenger numbers, performance and value for money. 
default4.7 
defaultThe number of passengers travelling using Community T
defaultransport in some districts/boroughs has declined; this is thought to be in part due to the impact of the provision of free transport on local 
defaultbus services. Older passengers, who make up the majority of community transport users, can travel on local buses f
defaultor free.  Though the cost of using community transport is subsidised, charges are 
defaultm
defaultade and passengers would like to be able to use their concessionary pass and travel for free.  Section 22 licences and registered bus services have allowed some of the sc
defaulthemes to introduce travel which is free to the users, being reimbursed by the concessionary fare scheme.
default4.8 
defaultCoverage by CT schemes is patchy – not all areas in need have a service. As schemes are independent there is no consistency in how they run and ope
defaultrate, although some flexibility is useful to account for local needs, a more consistent approach would 
defaulthelp users to better understand and access the services on offer. The fact that some schemes have Section 22 licences and allow passengers to use bus
default pas
defaultses while others don’t make 
defaultit confusing.  Consistent regulation would be 
defaultextremely 
defaultbeneficial
default.
default5.1 
defaultGiven the low number of individuals living in isolated communities providing services commercially is not an option and therefore will always be reliant on the local authority providing financial support for services.  This is not a 
defaultstatutory
default requirement a
defaultnd given the current economic pressures is becoming more challenging.
default5.2 
defaultTaxis are cost prohibitive for many people in isolated areas, plus there may be limited supply in some areas. Nor can concessionary passes be used in taxis. DRT can work very effecti
defaultvely in some areas
default where it is appropriate.
